== Required PPE ==
* Safety glasses
* ESD wrist strap (for ESD-sensitive work)
* Fume extractor or adequate ventilation
* Heat-resistant surface or silicone mat

== Soldering Iron Tip Selection ==
Select the tip shape and size based on the work:

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Tip Type !! Best For !! Notes
|-
| Chisel (screwdriver) || General through-hole, large SMD pads || Most versatile; good thermal transfer
|-
| Conical (pointed) || Fine-pitch SMD, tight spaces || Less thermal mass; slower heat transfer
|-
| Bevel || Drag soldering fine-pitch ICs || Flat face drags across pins evenly
|-
| Knife || Drag soldering, bridge cleanup || Angled edge for precision
|-
| Hoof (concave) || Drag soldering QFP/SOIC || Holds a small bead of solder in the concavity
|}

Use the largest tip that fits the work — larger tips transfer heat more efficiently and require lower temperatures.

== Temperature Guidelines ==
Use the lowest temperature that produces good joints efficiently. Excessive temperature accelerates tip oxidation and can damage components and pads.

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Solder Type !! Recommended Range !! Notes
|-
| Leaded (Sn63/Pb37) || 315-345C (600-650F) || Lower melting point; easier to work with
|-
| Lead-free (SAC305) || 345-385C (650-725F) || Higher melting point; use active flux
|-
| Fine-pitch SMD || 315-330C (600-625F) || Lower temp with good flux to avoid bridges
|-
| Large ground planes / connectors || 370-400C (700-750F) || Increase temp to overcome thermal mass
|}

== Procedure ==

=== Setup ===
# Power on the soldering station and set the desired temperature.
# Allow the iron to reach operating temperature (typically 30-60 seconds for cartridge-type irons).
# Tin the tip: apply a small amount of solder to the hot tip to create a shiny, wetted surface. This is essential for good heat transfer.
# Prepare your workspace: secure the PCB in a holder or vise, arrange components, and have solder, flux, and cleaning tools within reach.

=== Soldering a Through-Hole Joint ===
# Insert the component lead through the PCB hole.
# Touch the iron tip simultaneously to the pad and the component lead — heat both.
# After 1-2 seconds, feed solder into the joint (not onto the iron tip). The solder should flow and wick around the lead and pad.
# Remove the solder wire, then remove the iron. The joint should be shiny and concave (volcano-shaped).
# Trim the excess lead with flush cutters. Wear safety glasses — cut leads can fly.

=== Soldering SMD Components ===
# Apply flux to the pads.
# Tin one pad with a small amount of solder.
# Hold the component with tweezers, position it on the pads, and reflow the tinned pad to tack the component.
# Solder the remaining pad(s).
# Inspect under magnification for bridges, cold joints, or insufficient wetting.

=== Drag Soldering Fine-Pitch ICs ===
# Apply generous flux across all pads.
# Tack one corner pin to align the IC.
# Tack the diagonal corner pin to lock alignment.
# Apply solder to the tip and drag slowly across the pins. Flux prevents bridges.
# Inspect all pins under magnification. Use solder wick to remove any bridges.

=== Desoldering ===
# Apply flux to the joint.
# Heat the joint and use either:
#* '''Solder wick (braid):''' Press the wick onto the heated joint; it absorbs the molten solder via capillary action.
#* '''Solder sucker (desoldering pump):''' Heat the joint, then trigger the pump to vacuum up the molten solder.
# For SMD components, a hot air rework station is often more effective than an iron for desoldering.

== Tip Care ==
Tip life depends directly on maintenance. A well-maintained tip lasts significantly longer.

* '''Always keep the tip tinned.''' Before putting the iron in the stand, apply a fresh coat of solder to the tip. This prevents oxidation.
* '''Clean the tip frequently''' during use. Use a brass wool tip cleaner (preferred) or a damp cellulose sponge. Brass wool is less thermally shocking to the tip.
* '''Use the lowest effective temperature.''' High temperatures accelerate tip wear.
* '''Never file, sand, or scrape the tip.''' This destroys the iron plating and exposes the copper core.
* '''If a tip becomes black and won't accept solder:''' Apply tip tinner/activator (a flux-heavy paste) to restore wettability. If unrecoverable, replace the tip.
* '''Use setback/sleep features''' on your station to reduce tip temperature during idle periods.

== Workspace Setup ==
* Use a heat-resistant silicone mat or dedicated soldering surface.
* Secure PCBs in a PCB holder, helping-hands tool, or vise.
* Position a fume extractor 4-8 inches from the work area to capture flux fumes without disrupting the solder joint.
* Keep the soldering station away from the edge of the bench to prevent cord-pull accidents.
* Ensure a clear area around the iron stand — no papers, wires, or components that could contact the hot iron.

== Maintenance ==

=== After Each Session ===
* Tin the tip generously before powering off.
* Wipe down the iron stand and clean out any solder dross.
* Empty and clean the sponge or brass wool cleaner.

=== Periodically ===
* Inspect the iron cord and handle for heat damage.
* Verify tip-to-ground resistance is within spec (typically less than 2-5 ohms) using a multimeter. This protects ESD-sensitive components.
* Calibrate station temperature with a tip thermometer if available.
